== 2. Analyst

=== Hierarchy Level
2-4 years of experience, beginning to take ownership of specific stocks

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Stock Coverage*: Taking primary responsibility for 3-8 small/mid-cap stocks
- *Independent Research*: Conducting deep-dive analysis on companies, writing detailed research reports
- *Investment Ideas*: Generating investment recommendations (buy/hold/sell) with price targets
- *Company Engagement*: Leading meetings with smaller companies, building management relationships
- *Model Ownership*: Building and maintaining detailed financial models for coverage universe
- *Peer Review*: Quality checking and challenging research from graduate analysts
- *Sector Expertise*: Developing specialised knowledge in assigned sectors

=== Required Skills

*Technical:*
- Advanced financial modelling (complex capital structures, M&A scenarios)
- Deep accounting knowledge (identifying red flags, adjustments)
- Industry analysis frameworks (Porter's Five Forces, value chain analysis)
- Valuation across multiple methodologies (DCF, multiples, sum-of-parts)
- Understanding of corporate actions and capital management

*Interpersonal:*
- Confidence in presenting investment ideas
- Ability to engage with company management
- Intellectual curiosity and critical thinking
- Collaboration with portfolio managers and peers
- Professional skepticism in evaluating company narratives

*Regulatory:*
- ASX continuous disclosure and market announcements
- Takeover regulations and substantial shareholder notices
- Understanding of blackout periods and trading restrictions
- Awareness of material non-public information (MNPI) protocols

=== Typical Work Modes

*Analytical Work (55-65%):*
- Building and refining company models
- Writing investment recommendations and research reports
- Analysing industry trends and competitive dynamics
- Scenario analysis and stress testing assumptions

*Meetings (25-30%):*
- Company management meetings (1-on-1s, roadshows, conferences)
- Internal investment team discussions
- Broker-hosted events and sell-side analyst meetings
- Site visits and facility tours

*Presentations (10-15%):*
- Presenting stock ideas to Portfolio Managers
- Investment Committee presentations for new positions
- Participating in portfolio review discussions
- Educating team on sector developments

=== A Day in the Life

