=== A Day in the Life

*6:45am - 7:45am*: Early start to prepare for CSL results announcement this morning. Review final model, key metrics to watch, questions for management call. Send briefing note to Portfolio Manager highlighting 3 key issues: plasma collection volumes, margin trends, R&D pipeline updates.

*7:45am - 8:30am*: CSL announces results – beat on revenue, miss on margins due to plasma collection costs. Stock down 3% pre-market. Quickly update model with actual results, assess materiality of margin miss. Write initial assessment for PM: short-term margin pressure but doesn't change long-term thesis on plasma demand growth and pricing power.

*8:30am - 9:30am*: Listen to CSL management call. CEO and CFO discuss plasma collection strategy – increasing donor fees to rebuild collection network post-COVID. Your question to CFO: "Can you quantify the margin headwind from collection costs and when do you expect normalisation?" CFO guides to 12-18 month timeline for margin recovery. This confirms your view – temporary issue, not structural.

*9:30am - 10:30am*: Call with Portfolio Manager to discuss CSL position. You recommend holding position despite near-term margin pressure – thesis remains intact on long-term plasma shortage, new product pipeline looks strong, valuation now more attractive after today's sell-off. PM agrees, suggests potentially adding if stock weakens further.

*10:30am - 11:00am*: Review junior analyst's draft model on a mid-cap healthcare stock (Fisher & Paykel Healthcare). Provide detailed feedback on assumption methodology, suggest alternative approaches to modelling recurring revenue mix, highlight need for more robust sensitivity analysis. Schedule follow-up meeting to discuss.

*11:00am - 12:00pm*: Scheduled call with ResMed CEO discussing competitive dynamics in sleep apnea market. You've covered this space for 5 years and have strong relationship with management. Probe on GLP-1 drug impact on sleep apnea prevalence (emerging thesis you're developing), discuss home healthcare opportunity, get colour on European market recovery. Management pushing back on GLP-1 concerns – you remain cautious.

*12:00pm - 1:00pm*: Lunch meeting with industry expert consultant – former Cochlear executive now advising hearing aid manufacturers. Deep discussion on cochlear implant technology roadmap, bilateral implant trends, pricing dynamics across markets. Paid consultation arranged through compliance-approved channel. Valuable insights for refining Cochlear thesis.

*1:00pm - 2:00pm*: Write up detailed meeting notes from ResMed and Cochlear consultant calls. Key insight: GLP-1 weight loss drugs potentially reducing sleep apnea prevalence (negative for ResMed, CPR Sleep) but timeline uncertain. Flag this as emerging risk to monitor. Update internal research notes, share relevant points with PM.

*2:00pm - 3:30pm*: Work on major investment paper recommending new position in Ramsay Health Care. You've been building this thesis for 3 months – structural healthcare demand from aging population, underappreciated international growth potential, valuation compelling after 2-year de-rating. Draft executive summary, refine financial model, prepare risk factors section.

*3:30pm - 4:30pm*: Investment Committee presentation on existing large-cap holding (CSL). Present updated view post-results: maintain position, thesis intact, margin pressure temporary, valuation attractive at 26x forward PE vs 5-year average of 30x. Handle questions from PM and other sector analysts. Committee agrees to hold position, approved to add on further weakness.

*4:30pm - 5:30pm*: Mentoring session with junior analyst. Review their Sonic Healthcare model and investment thesis. Push them to think critically about structural shifts in pathology (home testing, AI diagnostics). Discuss how to develop differentiated views vs sell-side consensus. Career development discussion – they're ready to start leading coverage on small caps.

*5:30pm - 6:30pm*: Finish Ramsay Health Care investment paper for next week's Investment Committee. Finalise valuation work, complete competitive analysis section, refine investment thesis. Send to PM for initial review over weekend.

*Evening*: Leave office around 6:30-7:00pm. During non-results season, typically finish by 6pm. Results season and major project deadlines can extend to 8-9pm. Read research over dinner – reviewing competitor filings, reading healthcare trade publications, staying current on drug development pipeline news.

