=== A Day in the Life

*7:00am - 8:00am*: Review overnight global markets, key economic data releases, earnings announcements. Today: US Fed Chair testimony overnight (hawkish tilt), RBA meeting minutes released (more cautious on inflation), BHP production report (coal volumes miss). Draft key themes for this morning's research team meeting.

*8:00am - 9:00am*: Daily investment team meeting with CIO, all Portfolio Managers, sector heads. You present overview of overnight developments, facilitate discussion on RBA policy implications for domestic financials and consumer discretionary. Materials sector head presents initial BHP assessment (coal miss concerning but iron ore steady). Brief discussion on positioning ahead of US inflation data tomorrow.

*9:00am - 10:00am*: Strategic review meeting with CIO and Head of Portfolio Management. Discussing research function priorities for next 12 months: 1) Build out ESG integration framework (client demand increasing, consultant requirements tightening), 2) Enhance private markets research capability (superfunds allocating more to unlisted infrastructure/property), 3) Develop quantitative research support (alternative data sets, factor analysis). You propose hiring ESG specialist and quant researcher. CIO supportive but wants detailed business case.

*10:00am - 11:00am*: 1-on-1 meeting with Industrials sector head. Discussing two issues: 1) Underperformance in transport stocks (Qantas, Sydney Airport) – post-COVID recovery thesis not playing out, need to reassess. You challenge assumptions and push for deeper work on structural demand. 2) Promotion case for senior analyst to Lead Analyst role. You review performance, agree analyst is ready. Approve promotion effective next quarter.

*11:00am - 12:00pm*: Investment Committee presentation review – Materials sector head presenting major thesis on lithium oversupply risk. Paper recommends reducing exposure to Pilbara Minerals and Allkem. You've pre-read paper, have concerns about timing (spot prices already down 60%, may be pricing in oversupply). Challenge: "What's incremental catalyst for further downside? Aren't we late?" Discussion leads to more nuanced position: trim rather than exit, monitor Chinese demand data closely.

*12:00pm - 1:30pm*: Lunch meeting with consultant from Frontier Advisors conducting annual research review for large superfund client. They evaluate your research process, analyst quality, idea generation track record. You present research framework improvements made this year: enhanced ESG integration, implemented alternative data sources, strengthened emerging market research. Discussion on areas for improvement: could expand resources in technology sector (currently small cap only). Positive feedback overall but note consultant will write formal report with recommendations.

*1:30pm - 2:30pm*: Review session for upcoming major client presentation. You and CIO presenting to Aware Super's investment committee on Australian equities strategy. Review presentation deck: portfolio positioning, recent changes, market outlook, key stock ideas. You contribute research insights section – defensive positioning given late-cycle concerns, quality bias over value, selective growth opportunities in healthcare and industrials. Rehearse Q&A – they'll ask about performance vs benchmark, ESG integration, fintech disruption theme.

*2:30pm - 3:30pm*: Monthly research team all-hands meeting (all analysts, sector heads, quant team). Present firm performance update, market outlook, research priorities. Highlight excellent work by Consumer Discretionary team on Harvey Norman thesis (called margin recovery correctly). Announce new hires: ESG analyst joining next month, quant researcher in interview process. Open forum Q&A – analyst asks about coverage responsibilities for upcoming IPO pipeline. Discuss and agree on allocation.

*3:30pm - 4:30pm*: Investment Committee meeting. Major agenda items: 1) Lithium thesis review (trim positions approved), 2) New position proposal in Sonic Healthcare (you challenge pathology structural growth assumption, send back for more work), 3) Portfolio stress test results under recession scenario (review with CIO, comfortable with risk positioning). You flag emerging concern: portfolio underweight technology sector but mega-cap tech driving global indices – should we add technology analyst? Agree to explore.

*4:30pm - 5:30pm*: Interview with candidate for quant researcher role. Candidate has PhD in statistics, background at investment bank in systematic trading. You assess: 1) Technical capabilities (factor modelling, machine learning, time series analysis), 2) Ability to work with fundamental analysts (bridge quant and qualitative), 3) Cultural fit. Strong candidate. After interview, discuss with CIO – agree to make offer pending reference checks.

*5:30pm - 6:30pm*: Meeting with CCO (Chief Compliance Officer) and Head of Risk. Discussing implementation of new ASIC guidance on disclosure of ESG credentials. Implications for research process: need to document ESG analysis consistently, be cautious about "greenwashing" in company assessments, enhance training for analysts on ESG factors. You commit to developing standardised ESG research template and training program by quarter-end.

*6:30pm - 7:30pm*: Review and approve week's research output: investment papers from three analysts (approve two, send one back with feedback), quarterly sector updates from four sector heads (approve all with minor edits), thematic research piece on artificial intelligence implications for IT services sector (excellent work, approve for distribution to PMs and clients).

*Evening*: Leave around 7:30pm. Take home reading: detailed review of consultant report on research function (from last year's review) to identify improvement areas, industry white paper on ESG regulations in asset management, academic research on factor investing and style rotation. Weekend often includes thinking time on research strategy, reviewing critical investment papers, preparing for upcoming client presentations or Board meetings.

